Need more parse_string lines 780-816 full.































The crash is caused by an out-of-bounds read in `parse_string()` when parsing an unterminated JSON string.

Input:

```json
"abc
```

This starts a JSON string with `"`, but never closes it. The parser should reject the input cleanly. Instead, `parse_string()` scans forward looking for the closing quote without checking that it is still inside the input buffer before dereferencing the pointer.

The defective code is here:

```c
while (*input_end != '\"')
{
    /* is escape sequence */
    if (input_end[0] == '\\')
    {
        if ((size_t)(input_end + 1 - input_buffer->content) >= input_buffer->length)
        {
            /* prevent buffer overflow when last input character is a backslash */
            goto fail;
        }
        skipped_bytes++;
        input_end++;
    }
    input_end++;
}

if (((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) >= input_buffer->length) || (*input_end != '\"'))
{
    goto fail; /* string ended unexpectedly */
}
```

The bounds check happens after the loop, but the loop condition itself already dereferences `*input_end`. If no closing quote exists, `input_end` advances past the end of the allocated buffer and the next loop condition reads one byte out of bounds.

Step-by-step state:

1. `bench_driver.c` reads the input:

   ```c
   size_t n = fread(tmp, 1, sizeof(tmp), stdin);
   char *buf = malloc(n + 1);
   memcpy(buf, tmp, n);
   buf[n] = '\0';
   ```

   For input `"abc`, `n == 4`.

   The heap allocation has 5 bytes:

   ```text
   index:  0    1    2    3    4
   byte:   "    a    b    c   \0
   ```

2. `main()` calls:

   ```c
   cJSON_ParseWithOpts(buf, &err, 0);
   ```

3. `cJSON_ParseWithOpts()` computes:

   ```c
   buffer_length = strlen(value) + sizeof("");
   ```

   Since `strlen("\"abc") == 4` and `sizeof("") == 1`, `buffer_length == 5`.

   So the parser buffer covers the bytes:

   ```text
   "abc\0
   ```

4. `parse_value()` sees the first byte is `"`, so it calls:

   ```c
   parse_string(item, input_buffer);
   ```

5. In `parse_string()`:

   ```c
   const unsigned char *input_pointer = buffer_at_offset(input_buffer) + 1;
   const unsigned char *input_end = buffer_at_offset(input_buffer) + 1;
   ```

   Since `buffer_at_offset(input_buffer)` points at the opening quote, both `input_pointer` and `input_end` initially point at the `a`.

6. The loop searches for the terminating quote:

   ```c
   while (*input_end != '\"')
   ```

   It visits:

   ```text
   input_end -> 'a'   not quote, increment
   input_end -> 'b'   not quote, increment
   input_end -> 'c'   not quote, increment
   input_end -> '\0'  not quote, increment
   input_end -> one past allocation
   ```

7. The next evaluation of:

   ```c
   *input_end
   ```

   reads one byte past the heap allocation. AddressSanitizer reports this as a heap buffer overflow.

The root cause is not the malformed input itself. Malformed JSON should produce a parse failure. The root cause is that `parse_string()` dereferences `input_end` before proving that `input_end` is still within `input_buffer->length`.

A minimal local fix is to add a bounds check to the loop condition before dereferencing `input_end`:

```c
while (((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) < input_buffer->length) &&
       (*input_end != '\"'))
{
    /* is escape sequence */
    if (input_end[0] == '\\')
    {
        if ((size_t)(input_end + 1 - input_buffer->content) >= input_buffer->length)
        {
            /* prevent buffer overflow when last input character is a backslash */
            goto fail;
        }
        skipped_bytes++;
        input_end++;
    }
    input_end++;
}

if (((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) >= input_buffer->length) ||
    (*input_end != '\"'))
{
    goto fail; /* string ended unexpectedly */
}
```

Because `||` short-circuits, the post-loop check remains safe: if `input_end` is out of range, `*input_end` is not evaluated.

A cleaner version avoids repeating the pointer arithmetic inline:

```c
while ((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) < input_buffer->length)
{
    if (*input_end == '\"')
    {
        break;
    }

    if (*input_end == '\\')
    {
        if ((size_t)(input_end + 1 - input_buffer->content) >= input_buffer->length)
        {
            goto fail;
        }

        skipped_bytes++;
        input_end++;
    }

    input_end++;
}

if (((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) >= input_buffer->length) ||
    (*input_end != '\"'))
{
    goto fail; /* string ended unexpectedly */
}
```

That fixes the immediate heap overflow.

A more thorough root-cause fix would be to make all string scanning in `parse_string()` consistently length-based instead of sentinel-based. JSON strings are not C strings; they are ranges inside a parse buffer. The parser should never rely on eventually finding either `"` or `'\0'`. Every read from `input_pointer`, `input_end`, or escape lookahead positions should be guarded by `input_buffer->length`.

For example, the first scan can be structured as:

```c
const unsigned char * const buffer_end =
    input_buffer->content + input_buffer->length;

while (input_end < buffer_end)
{
    if (*input_end == '\"')
    {
        break;
    }

    if (*input_end == '\\')
    {
        if ((input_end + 1) >= buffer_end)
        {
            goto fail;
        }

        skipped_bytes++;
        input_end++;
    }

    input_end++;
}

if ((input_end >= buffer_end) || (*input_end != '\"'))
{
    goto fail;
}
```

This makes the parser’s invariant explicit: `input_end` may only be dereferenced while `input_end < buffer_end`.

The benchmark driver is mostly doing the right thing by allocating `n + 1` and NUL-terminating the input. However, since it already knows the exact number of bytes read, it would be preferable for a fuzzing or benchmark driver to call the length-aware API directly:

```c
cJSON *item = cJSON_ParseWithLengthOpts(buf, n, &err, 0);
```

or, if the parser expects the terminating NUL to be included:

```c
cJSON *item = cJSON_ParseWithLengthOpts(buf, n + 1, &err, 0);
```

But that does not replace the parser fix. Even with the length-aware API, `parse_string()` must not read past `input_buffer->length`.

##### Recommendation

Fix `parse_string()` so the search for the closing quote checks the parse-buffer bounds before dereferencing `input_end`:

```c
while (((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) < input_buffer->length) &&
       (*input_end != '\"'))
{
    if (input_end[0] == '\\')
    {
        if ((size_t)(input_end + 1 - input_buffer->content) >= input_buffer->length)
        {
            goto fail;
        }
        skipped_bytes++;
        input_end++;
    }
    input_end++;
}

if (((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) >= input_buffer->length) ||
    (*input_end != '\"'))
{
    goto fail;
}
```

Additionally, consider changing the driver to use the length-aware API:

```c
cJSON *item = cJSON_ParseWithLengthOpts(buf, n, &err, 0);
```

but the parser-side bounds check is the actual required fix.

